{"title":"Hearing Touch: Audio-Visual Pretraining for Contact-Rich Manipulation","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Robotic manipulation in low-data regimes benefits from tactile sensing, but large-scale pretraining exists mainly for vision. Collecting internet-scale tactile datasets is impractical, and vision alone struggles to perceive subtle contact events, limiting generalization.","method":"Use piezo contact microphones on the robot gripper to capture contact-rich vibrations as audio and transfer internet-scale audio-visual pretraining to this modality. Initialize the audio encoder with AVID pre-trained on Audioset and the visual encoder with R3M; keep both unfrozen during policy learning. Train an end-to-end behavior cloning policy that fuses audio and vision via self-attention to predict actions. This is, to the authors’ knowledge, the first use of large-scale multisensory (audio-visual) pretraining for manipulation and yields substantial gains over vision-only and audio-from-scratch/BYOL-A baselines across three real tasks, with improved robustness to large visual domain shifts."},{"problem":"Fusing time-synchronized vision and contact audio into stable yet reactive manipulation actions is challenging, especially when demonstrations are non-Markovian and contact cues are subtle and fast.","method":"Preprocess 2-second windows of averaged contact-mic audio into mel spectrograms and pair them with 4 synchronized images. Encode each stream with pretrained encoders, add learned positional embeddings, and fuse with a transformer self-attention block. Predict short-horizon sequences of 6-DoF delta end-effector actions and execute h steps before replanning (quasi open-loop) to remain responsive to audio while ensuring temporal consistency. Ablations show self-attention fusion is crucial and pretrained audio features transfer well—even when frozen—highlighting the effectiveness of the fusion design and pretraining choices."}]}
